Landing.ColumnBanner.BuildModelsDescript: Model a multitude of biological processes, including metabolic networks, gene regulation, signal transduction, cell-cell interaction networks, food webs, etc. related to various organisms ranging from bacteria to viruses to flies to plants to humans. Define models without the need to enter or modify complex mathematical equations.
Landing.ColumnBanner.PerformSimulationsD: Use real-time, interactive simulations to visualize the dynamics of the biological process under various extracellular as well as mutational (i.e., diseased) conditions. Run hundreds of simulation experiments in a matter of minutes and perform input-output analysis to visualize cellular responses under different conditions
Landing.ColumnBanner.AnalyzeResultsDescr: Analyze the dynamics and responses of biological systems under different conditions. Run system-wide perturbation analyses to predict and rank the effects of individual and combinations of components on the system. Predict and explore drug re-purposing and combinatorial therapy opportunities.
Landing.VideoBanner.VideoBannerDescripti: Students no longer need to memorize biological concepts - they can model and simulate the dynamical interactions instead using Cell Collective modeling software.
Landing.VideoBanner.VideoBannerStudentMe: I found that by actually doing these types of simulations, I understand the concepts a lot more afterwards.
Landing.VideoBanner.VideoBannerStudentTi: Student of Biological Sciences, University of Nebraska-Lincoln
LandingPage.UniversityBanner.UniversityB: From Researchers, to the World's Top Universities
1000s of researchers, teachers and students across the world use Cell Collective to learn, build and simulate biological models.
If you have questions, please contact us at support@cellcollective.org.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase1.ClickOn: Click on {photo} icon to create a new model
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase1.BrowseC: Browse the Catalog of Available Models
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase1.Publish:
• PUBLISHED MODELS are peer-reviewed, published models made available to the Cell Collective community for simulations and further contributions.
  • MY MODELS contain models constructed and owned by you.
  • SHARED WITH ME are models that other users shared directly with you. Use this feature to directly build and analyze models with your collaborators (without sending model SBML files back and forth).
  • Scroll Right to see more Models!
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase1.YouMayC: You may click the {photo} icon at any time to learn about the many features of Cell Collective.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsModelPhase1.ClickO: Click on the icon to switch between {photo1} (View Mode) and {photo2} (Edit Mode). Double Click on an empty space to add a new component. Double Click Label to rename component. Shift + Right-click component to switch between internal or external components. Switch between positive or negative interaction by Shift + left-clicking the connecting line.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsModelPhase1.NewMod: New model components may also be added by clicking here on {photo}. Double-click label to edit component name.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsModelPhase1.ToAddA: To add an activator or inhibitor, drag and drop components from the list of Internal Components or External Components to the appropriate Drop Component dialogue box.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsModelPhase1.ClickO: Click on {photo} icon to save your changes.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsSimulationPhase1.U: Use the simple slider to set the external conditions (i.e. the simulation inputs). Levels may also be varied during a simulation to visualize changes in the dynamics of the system in real-time. This is analogous with varying the environment of a biological system and observing its response.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsSimulationPhase1.S: Select the checkbox  below the visibility {photo} icon for the components you want to visualize on the Simulation Graph. Hovering over the component label will highlight its trendline, allowing you to quickly locate the component within a busy graph!
Dashboard.joyrideStepsSimulationPhase1.C: Click {photo1} icon to start the simulation. You may also click {photo2} to pause the simulation at any time or reset the simulation by clicking on {photo3} icon.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsAnalysisPhase1.Cli: Click on {photo} icon to create a new experiment. Experiments are renamed directly by clicking on the label.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsAnalysisPhase1.Use: Use the simple slider to set the external conditions (i.e. the simulation inputs) for the experiment. This is analogous with setting the external signals a biological system encounters within its environment, influencing its biological response.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsAnalysisPhase1.Cli: Click on  {photo} iicon to start the simulation.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsAnalysisPhase1.Dos: Dose-response graphs may be generated for any component in the model by selecting the appropriate component for the X and Y-axis. In general, an external component is represented on the X-axis (the pendent variable) whereas internal components are represented on the Y-axis (the dependent variables). Multiple dose-response curves may be generated from a single experiment.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase2.YouMayS: You may search for models by title, description, tags or protein name. A single query will search the Published Models, My Models, and Shared with Me catalogs concurrently.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase2.ChangeB: Change between List and Grid View
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase2.YouCanC: You can change your view between list view and grid view.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsHomePhase2.InThisM: In this menu you can edit your user profile, change your password, and logout.
JoyDashboardRide.joyrideStepsModelPhase2: Conditions (or SubConditions) are used to model cooperative or disjointed dependencies between one or more interacting partners. Click on add icon to open the Conditions panel, drag and drop the appropriate components to the (drop component) dialogue box and specify if the Condition must be Active or Inactive.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsModelPhase2.ClickO: Models are annotated and referenced using the Knowledge Base. Click on {photo1} to add content and {photo2} to add references. Simply enter the PubMed Identifier (PMID) to seamlessly format and integrate citations. References may be tagged according to publication and data type. Simply right-click on the reference and select the tag you want to add.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsModelPhase2.Collab: Collaboration is key to new discoveries using the systems approach - and is at the heart of Cell Collective! Clicking on {photo} takes you to the Share page, enabling you to add collaborators, create shareable links and publish experiments.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsModelPhase2.Select: Select the component you would like to mutate. Clicking the box once is a loss-of-function mutation (indicated by a red checkmark), and clicking the box twice is a gain-of-function mutation (indicated by a green checkmark). Clicking through a third time removes the mutation. Mutations may be introduced before or during a simulation to visualize changes on the dynamics in real-time.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsSimulationPhase2.C: Click {photo} to create an initial state. Once an initial state is created, the  icon is displayed within the Internal Components panel. From this column, select the components you want active at the beginning of a simulation (t=0).

Click {photo} to record a simulation flow. The icon will turn green once the recording is in progress. Changes in experimental conditions or mutations, and their respective time-point interval occurrences, are recorded and saved within a simulation flow, enabling re-running of preset experiments.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsAnalysisPhase2.Mul: Multiple experiments may be selected using the checkboxes. Once selected, you may remove, copy, or re-run the experiments simultaneously. This is especially useful for updating experiments after making a change to a modelâ€™s regulatory mechanism.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsAnalysisPhase2.Col: Click {photo} next to Simulation Flow: label to create a simulation flow. Analysis simulation flows cannot be recorded, therefore, the external conditions (i.e. inputs) or mutations, and their range (i.e. time-point occurrences) must be pre-defined manually. Read the tutorial Simulation Flows for more details.
Dashboard.joyrideStepsAnalysisPhase2.Onc: Once you have a graph presented here you can download the Activity Relationship Graph as a PNG file by clicking here.
ModelDashBoard.Views.DominanceGraphViewD: Displays dominance graph for given component using green nodes for positive and red nodes for negative regulators. Edge between given negative and positive regulator means that this negative regulator is dominant over that positive one.
ModelDashBoard.Views.ComponentGraphViewD: Displays network of components regulated by given component.
ModelDashBoard.Views.ModelGraphViewDescr: Displays model network using green edges for positive, red edges for negative regulators and yellow nodes for external components.
